{"person":{"id":"HD3923","former_ids":[],"is_placeholder":false,"has_descendants_documented":true,"bio":{"title":"Captain","first_name":"Henry","middle_name":"Hobart","last_name":"Stiles","married_names":[],"gender":"male","display_name":"Captain Henry Hobart Stiles","photo_url":"https://res.cloudinary.com/dc5clrqtw/image/upload/v1778520603/henryhstiles_nug49y.png"},"birth":{"year":1824,"month":10,"day":4,"city":"North Haven","county":"New Haven","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"baptism":{},"death":{"year":1878,"month":4,"city":"North Haven","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"residence":{"city":"North Haven","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"burial":{},"classification":{"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_thomas_spouse":false,"is_talcott_spouse":false,"generation_from_thomas":8,"include_in_path_calculation":true,"descent_paths_to_thomas":1,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"is_progenitor":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"parents":{"father_id":"H01182","mother_id":"I00524"},"number_of_marriages":1,"marriages":[{"marriage_number":1,"spouse_id":"I00520","date_year":1845,"date_month":10,"date_day":15,"location_city":"North Haven","location_state":"Connecticut","location_country":"United States","end_type":"death","end_year":1878,"children_ids":["HD3924","HD3925","HD3926","HD3927","HD3928"]}],"education":[],"career":[{"role":"Brick yard manager","location":"Haddam, Connecticut","start_year":1842,"notes":"Per Stiles book #953: 'when eighteen years old went to Haddam, Conn., to take charge of a brick yard.'"},{"role":"Partner, brickmaker","organization":"I. L. Stiles & Son","location":"North Haven, Connecticut","end_year":1878,"notes":"Brick manufacturing business with his brother Isaac Lorenzo Stiles (Stiles book #950)."},{"role":"Captain, North Haven Rifles","organization":"North Haven Rifles","location":"North Haven, Connecticut","notes":"Local militia company. The title 'Captain' by which he was ever afterwards designated derived from this command, predating his Civil War commission."},{"role":"State Representative","organization":"Connecticut General Assembly","location":"Hartford, Connecticut","start_year":1855,"notes":"Three terms from 1855."},{"role":"Selectman + Town Agent","organization":"Town of North Haven, Connecticut","location":"North Haven, Connecticut","end_year":1862,"notes":"Resigned in August 1862 to enlist in Civil War."}],"military_service":[{"war":"American Civil War","war_id":"WAR006","rank":"Captain (Co. K 15th CT Vol Inf, then Co. B 21st Veteran Reserve Corps)","rank_year_start":1862,"rank_year_end":1865,"unit":"15th Connecticut Volunteer Infantry, Co. K (commission dated Aug 1, 1862); then 21st Veteran Reserve Corps, Co. B (Dec 1863)","notes":"Enlisted Aug 9, 1862 New Haven CT; elected Captain of Co. K, 15th Connecticut Volunteers (commission Aug 1, 1862). Engaged at the Battle of Fredericksburg (December 1862, BTL026), at Edenton Road, Providence Church, and skirmishes near Norfolk Virginia. Honorable discharge for ill health Aug 17, 1863. Returned to service December 1863 as Captain of Co. B, 21st Regiment Veteran Reserve Corps, assigned to Providence Rhode Island as Post Commandant. In March 1864 removed with his company to Albany New York where he commanded the Rendezvous Camp. While there he organized, armed, and equipped the 192nd New York State Volunteers. Acting Post Commissary, Quartermaster, and command of two companies — these arduous duties broke his health again, and he resigned his commission Aug 1, 1865. On separation, his commands presented him with an inscribed sword, a heavy gold-headed cane, a costly jewelled watch and chain, field-glasses, and revolvers."}],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"artworks":[],"tags":["civil_war","state_representative"],"research_tags":[],"cross_connections":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"military","header":"Captain at Fredericksburg, organized 192nd New York, 1864","body":"Stiles enlisted at New Haven Aug 9, 1862 and was elected captain of Co. K, 15th Connecticut Volunteers, serving at the Battle of Fredericksburg in December 1862. Discharged for ill health, he returned as captain of the 21st Veteran Reserve Corps and commanded the Rendezvous Camp at Albany New York in 1864, where he organized, armed, and equipped the 192nd New York State Volunteers."},{"category":"death","header":"Knew the end was approaching in fall 1877","body":"The Stiles Family in America entry 953 records: 'In the fall of 1877, he fully realized that the end of his life was approaching, and prepared his business as he thought best.' He died at North Haven in April 1878 at age fifty-three.","number":2},{"category":"career","header":"Brick yard at eighteen made the man","body":"At eighteen in 1842 he went to Haddam Connecticut to take charge of a brick yard. The Stiles book notes that 'the position developed the character that he afterwards sustained through life'; he returned home to partner with brother Isaac Lorenzo as I L Stiles & Son, brickmakers.","number":3},{"category":"military","header":"Troops parted with sword, cane, jewelled watch","body":"When he resigned his commission at Albany in August 1865 from arduous duties as Post Commandant and Quartermaster, his commands presented him with an inscribed sword, a heavy gold-headed cane, a jewelled watch and chain, field-glasses, and revolvers. The 192nd New York Volunteers had been organized, armed, and equipped under his command at the Rendezvous Camp.","number":4}],"quotes":[],"sources":[{"label":"The Stiles Family in America (BIB008) entry #953"}],"research_sources":[{"bib_id":"BIB008"}],"documents":[],"slug":"henry-stiles-1824"},"neighborhood":{"focus":{"id":"HD3923","slug":"henry-stiles-1824","n":"Captain Henry Hobart Stiles","by":1824,"dy":1878,"sx":"u","hd":true,"td":false,"ee":false,"g":8},"spouses":[{"order":1,"spouse":{"id":